<showme.pack xmlns="Compositor"
             xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance"
             id="Exa_SequenceConverge1"
             xsi:schemaLocation="Compositor file:/C:/xampp/htdocs/moodle2.5/mod/msm/XSLTdocuments/Compositor.xsd">
	  <texsupport href="../Analysis_TeXSupport.xml"/>
	
	  <title>Convergent Sequences: Examples</title>
	  <showme>
		    <statement.showme>
			      <para>
            <para.body>Show that the sequence <math>
                  <latex>(x_n)</latex>
               </math> with <math>
                  <latex>x_n = 1/n</latex>
               </math> converges to <math>
                  <latex>0</latex>
               </math>.</para.body>
         </para>
		    </statement.showme>
		    <answer.showme type="Solution">
         <answer.showme.block>
            <answer.showme.block.body>
			            <para>
                  <para.body>Let <math>
                        <latex> \varepsilon &gt; 0 </latex>
                     </math> be given. We need to find some <math>
                        <latex> n_0 &gt; 0 </latex>
                     </math> such that</para.body>
               </para>
			            <math.display>
				              <latex> \Abs{ \frac{1}{n} - 0 } &lt; \varepsilon</latex>
			            </math.display>
			            <para>
                  <para.body>for all <math>
                        <latex>n\geq n_0</latex>
                     </math>. To establish the existence of such <math>
                        <latex>n_0</latex>
                     </math> recall that 
				<subordinate>
                        <hot>
                           <math>
                              <latex>\NNr</latex>
                           </math> is not bounded above</hot>
                        <crossref>
                           <theorem.ref theoremID="Thm_NNotBoundedAbove"/>
                           <info>
						
						                        <para>
                                 <para.body>Look up this fact.</para.body>
                              </para>
					                      </info>
                        </crossref>
                     </subordinate>. Therefore there exists <math>
                        <latex>n_0\in \NNr</latex>
                     </math> with <math>
                        <latex> 0 &lt; 1/\varepsilon &lt; n_0 </latex>
                     </math>. Now, if <math>
                        <latex>n\geq n_0</latex>
                     </math>, we 
				<subordinate>
                        <hot>find</hot>
                        <crossref>
                           <theorem.ref theoremID="Thm_ROrderingProperties"/>
                           <info>
						
						                        <para>
                                 <para.body>Look up this fact.</para.body>
                              </para>
					                      </info>
                        </crossref>
                     </subordinate>
			               </para.body>
               </para>
			            <math.display>
				              <latex> 0 &lt; \dfrac{1}{n} \leq \dfrac{1}{n_0} &lt; \dfrac{1}{1/\varepsilon} = \varepsilon </latex>
			            </math.display>
			            <para>
                  <para.body>This means that <math>
                        <latex> -\varepsilon &lt; 1/x_n - 0 &lt; \varepsilon </latex>
                     </math> or, equivalently, <math>
                        <latex> \Abs{ 1/n - 0 } &lt; \varepsilon </latex>
                     </math> whenever <math>
                        <latex>n\geq n_0</latex>
                     </math>. Therefore <math>
                        <latex>(1/n)</latex>
                     </math> converges to <math>
                        <latex>0</latex>
                     </math> or, in symbols,</para.body>
               </para>
			            <math.display>
				              <latex>\lim_{n\to\infty} \dfrac{1}{n}\ =\ 0.</latex>
			            </math.display>
		          </answer.showme.block.body>
         </answer.showme.block>
      </answer.showme>
	  </showme>
</showme.pack>
